Here, we describe the synthesis of graphene–fullerol covalent hybrid (GFL) by impregnating and heating the individual counterparts (Fig. 1
                  ). This approach allows to prepare conductive hybrid (0.8×105
                  Sm−1); such conductivities have been attained only in graphene or non-covalently functionalized graphene derivatives [17]. Moreover, compared to other previously reported nanobuds based on the covalent attachment of fullerene to graphene or CNTs [7–9], the GFL hybrid exhibits aqueous dispersibility owing to fullerol species (0.04mgmL−1). Finally, –OH/–O− groups in the fullerol structure promote the electrochemical response through hydrogen bonding or electrostatic interactions towards sensed biomolecules.
